# Decide the Gateway Redis Channel's Fate

## Question

Joel (2026-07-13, post-storm): "worth thinking if this needs to exist in our
world today with herdr observer running." The gateway redis channel was the
pre-herdr reflex arc: realtime signals (slack.signal.received, front
non-VIP notifies) queued in unTTL'd Redis lists to wake the interactive
ShitRat gateway persona. In today's world: memory is the observer's job
(30-min batch, durable pages), interaction is herdr sessions + the phone
line, and Redis-lists-as-pseudo-memory is exactly the unowned state the
storm grew in. Decide: (a) what genuinely needs REALTIME reflex (VIP email,
urgent pages) vs what is now observer/batch territory; (b) whether the
reflex arc's target should become "wake the right herdr session"
(herdr agent send) instead of a bespoke gateway loop; (c) retirement or
slimming path for the redis channel, with the storm-budget code kept
wherever pub/sub survives. Adjacent to the Observer/Bugle boundary grilling
— same redistricting, interaction lane.

## Answer (2026-07-13, grilled with Joel)

**(b) Wake, dont feed — with the dispatcher inside the observer session.**

1. The reflex arc shrinks to ROUTING. A small classifier agent — terra on
   LOW effort, tuned for classification + system routing — runs as a
   dedicated pane in the observer herdr session (Joels refinement). Signals
   flow to it; it decides: wake a herdr session (herdr agent send), page
   Joel (joelclaw notify), or drop-to-batch (the observer will see it).
2. Context never rides the signal. A woken session gets "you were woken
   because X; recall has the rest" — memory is the only context assembler.
   No prompt injection, no Redis-lists-as-pseudo-memory.
3. Tiny reflex allowlist: VIP email, direct invokes/@mentions,
   telemetry-watch anomalies (paging grade). Everything else is observer
   food on the 30-minute lane.
4. Transport slims: thin Redis pub/sub into the dispatcher, every list
   TTLd, emission-budget code guards it. The always-on gateway personas
   prompt-feeding loop (drainEvents → enqueuePrompt) retires once the
   dispatcher lands.

Graduates: build-observer-dispatcher; retire-gateway-prompt-loop.
